Risk of Credit Default







MoneyPenny’s is a new online lending business. They have to make a decision as to which consumer to lend based on the information that MoneyPenny’s have about them. MoneyPenny’s have agreed with a credit bureau on data sharing and they intend to make their decision based on this data. Below a short summary of the data:

data <- read_csv('bureau_data.csv')
dict <- read_csv('dict.csv')

Visualisations

As is usually the case, there is a strong class imbalance in the data. Customers who have a history of default on loan repayment are far less numerous than those who repay their loans in full. This usually presents problems for algorithms as there isn’t enough information on the minority class to learn the optimal weights which would make a robust classifier.

data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Target, fill = factor(Target))) +
  geom_bar() +
   labs(x= "Default",
       title = "Imbalance of Classes",
       colour = 'Target') +
    scale_fill_viridis_d(option = 'cividis',
                         name = "Target") +
    theme_ipsum()

Exploring some variables distributions across classes helps understanding the data a bit further. We have picked two continuous variables (Var13, Var14) and plotted them on the x and y axis along with their marginal distributions. These plots help confirm that in the case of these two variables, we observe a similar distribution across classes (default and non-default classes). Of course, we observe marginal distributions in the minority class which show just how less information we have about it compared to the majority class.

Model

Based on the requirements of MoneyPenny’s, we built a classifier using a boosted trees model using XGBoost. We have approached the problem of not having test or validation sets by pursuing a 5-fold crossvalidation on the training data. Concomitantly, optimal hyperparameters were sought through a random search. We sought to reduce logloss with a logistic objective function. We addressed class imbalance by weighting the data according to the proportion of the majority class over the minority class.

To this end, we have cleaned the data removing variables with only one value, recodified categorical variables into one-hot encoding and rescaled variables between 0 and 1. Needless to say that more knowledge about the data would help the modelling process greatly and that only true portfolio performance will put the model to the true test.

modellingData <- function(data, dict){
  
  cleanData <- 
  data %>% 
    select(-`...1`, -ID) %>% 
    mutate(across(.cols = starts_with('Var'),
                  .fns = ~ scales::rescale(., to = c(0,1)))) %>% 
    fastDummies::dummy_cols(remove_selected_columns = T,
                            select_columns = dict$Var[dict$Type == "Categorical Nominal" | 
                                                        dict$Type == "Categorical Ordinal"],
                            remove_first_dummy = T
    )
  
  return(cleanData)
}

dataForMOdelling <- modellingData(data, dict)

makeXGBMatrix <- function(data) {
  
  weight <- sum(data$Target == 0) / sum(data$Target == 1) 
  
  trainMatrix <- 
    data %>% 
    select(-Target) %>% 
    as.matrix()
  
  trainMatrix <-
    apply(trainMatrix, 2, as.numeric)
  
  xgbtrainMatrix <- 
    xgb.DMatrix(data = trainMatrix,
                label = data %>% select(Target) %>% unlist)
  
  return(list(trainMatrix = trainMatrix,
              xgbtrainMatrix = xgbtrainMatrix,
              weight = weight))
  
} 

inputs <- makeXGBMatrix(dataForMOdelling)

searchXGB <- function(inputs){
  
  # random search best xgb hyperparams, keeps best result
  
  min_test_loss = Inf
  best_test_loss = Inf
  best_params = list()
  
  for(i in 1:10){
    
    # random setting of hyperparams
    params = list(
      booster = 'gbtree',
      eta = runif(1, 0.01, 0.4),
      max_depth = sample(6:10, 1),
      lambda = runif(1, .01, 1),
      alpha = runif(1,0.1,1),
      gamma = runif(1, 0, 5),
      subsample = runif(1, .5, 1),
      colsample_bytree = runif(1, .5, .8),
      objective = 'binary:logistic',
      eval_metric = 'logloss',
      scale_pos_weight = inputs$weight
    )
    
    # 5 fold cv training 
    iterXGB <- xgb.cv(
      data = inputs$xgbtrainMatrix,
      params = params,
      nfold = 5,
      verbose = 2,
      early_stopping_rounds = 30,
      maximize = F,
      nrounds = 10000,
      showsd = T,
      print_every_n = 10,
      stratified = T
    )

    min_test_loss <-
      if_else(
        iterXGB$evaluation_log[iterXGB$best_iteration]$test_logloss_mean < min_test_loss,
        iterXGB$evaluation_log[iterXGB$best_iteration]$test_logloss_mean,
        min_test_loss)
    
    # update global results and retain all things needed
    if(min_test_loss < best_test_loss){
      best_test_loss <- min_test_loss
      best_params <- params
    }
    
  }
  
  finalXGB <-
    xgb.train(
      params = best_params,
      nrounds = 20000,
      data = inputs$xgbtrainMatrix,
      verbose = 2,
      maximize = F,
      early_stopping_rounds = 5,
      watchlist = list(train = inputs$xgbtrainMatrix)
    )
    
  return(list(
    iterXGB = iterXGB,
    finalXGB = finalXGB,
    best_params = best_params)
    )  
}

XGBoutput <- searchXGB(inputs)

Model Evaluation

Below a visualisation of mean test logloss falling throughout training iterations. As expected loss falls as the models learns from the data. In this case, the test set is made of a fifth of the data selected at random in a stratified way according to the label proportion:

XGBoutput$iterXGB$evaluation_log %>% 
  ggplot(aes(iter,
             train_logloss_mean)) +
  geom_point(colour='#00008b') +
  labs(title = "Crossvalidation Logloss",
       y = 'mean logloss',
       x = 'iteration') +
  theme_ipsum() +
  theme(legend.position="none")

Finally, to assess this model’s performance we can visualise classification through a confusion matrix. This is indeed a satisfactory result, however the true test will come at production time.

cm <- 
  as.data.frame(ModelMetrics::confusionMatrix(dataForMOdelling$Target,
                              predict(XGBoutput$finalXGB,
                                      inputs$trainMatrix)))


names(cm) <- c("Observed Negatives", "Observed Positives")
rownames(cm) <- c("Predicted Negatives", "Predicted Positives")

cm %>% 
  kbl() %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 14, latex_options = "scale_down")
